						               													<description>Shootin Iron is a fast-playing miniature game designed for tournament play or pick-up games.  The goal of these rules isn't to simulate realism, but rather to allow you to play out cinematic Wild West shootouts using smart tactics and no small bit of luck.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;mdash;description from the introduction&amp;#10;&amp;#10;This concise miniatures game shares some cosmetic elements with Shotguns -n- Saddles, (the roleplaying game); however, it is a standalone  miniatures combat game.  The play surface is suggested as 3' x 3', with at least some indication of terrain.  The game assumes figures will be used to denote participating units.  Ranges are given in inches and play assumes the use of a tape measure.  Resolution requires a D6 and a D8.  The game rules primarily deal with fire and movement (as you would expect).  The default starting situation finds two opposing teams (&amp;quot;posse&amp;quot;) of six fighters each.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game is played in rounds; during each round each participant takes a turn.  Turns are executed in specified order and effects take place immediately.  Units utilize a simple facing mechanic and gain benefits depending on type.  Some complicating rules (e.g., &amp;quot;town folk&amp;quot;) are optional.  The rules are presented as a single, color PDF document - included are the rules, optional rules, and twelve scenarios (eleven are standard westerns; one is a weird western (zombies).&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;mdash;user summary&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
